description:
The US plan to end Israel’s war on Gaza is designed, supervised and administered “primarily by people who are very staunchly pro-Israel,” and has little chance of delivering peace, argues Stephen Walt, professor of international relations at Harvard University.

“We’ve seen this movie before,” Walt tells host Steve Clemons. According to the terms announced by US President Donald Trump, Israel can argue at any time that the Palestinian side isn’t fulfilling its obligations and thus resume the war.

Increasingly seen as a threat by other countries in the region, Israel “is in for a very troubling future”, Walt says.

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
Some people here are very careful about expressing their excitement or expressing their true feelings about what’s going on. They’ve been let down so many times to the point they don’t believe it.

People, initially, responded with excitement.

They stay hopeful, and they pray that they are going to get to that point where there is a public announcement, because that would give them a respite, that would give them a proper moment to mourn the past 729 days – and the constant displacement, constant trauma, constant fear.

There was instruction earlier telling the Israeli military to move from offensive mode into defensive mode, but three of the attacks on Gaza today happened right after this statement was made – and that’s what makes the whole feeling here still a bit shaky.

Meanwhile, we’re not seeing any concrete movement on the ground in terms of withdrawal from areas that have been occupied by the Israeli military over the past few days.

Al Jazeera’s Hani Mahmoud reports.

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
In this special episode, we examine the systematic targeting of Palestinian journalists in Gaza during two years of Israeli genocide. With international media barred from freely reporting in the Strip, local journalists have risked their lives to document the unprecedented killing, destruction and displacement around them.

Since October 7, 2023, more media workers have been killed in Gaza than in any modern conflict. Families have been torn apart, homes and offices destroyed, and reporters have been wounded, seen their families killed or have been killed themselves.

This episode reveals the extraordinary playbook employed by Israel to threaten, intimidate, smear and target Palestinian journalists.

Contributors:
Wael Dahdouh – Gaza Bureau Chief, Al Jazeera
Jodie Ginsberg – Chief Executive, Committee to Protect Journalists
Sharif Abdel Kouddous – Journalist & Editor, Drop Site News
Rachel Shabi – Journalist and author

Presenter: Richard Gizbert
Produced by: Soumaya El Filali, Monazz
title: Smear. Kill. Repeat. | The Listening Post

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
Sami Al-Arian, a professor of public affairs at Istanbul Zaim University, says President Trump’s plan included most of the main topics of negotiations over Gaza – such as the exchange of Palestinian prisoners and Israeli captives in return for ending the war, the withdrawal of the Israeli army, as well as the return of aid into Gaza and the reconstruction of the enclave.

He stressed that the part on the Israeli military’s withdrawal was “very vague” and was the main discussion point in the negotiations, in a reminder that most of the talks failed in the past over this element.

“Trump also included parts on the future of Gaza in his plan,” said Al-Arian, adding that Hamas absolved itself from delivering an opinion on the future of Gaza by saying that it should be a collective Palestinian decision.

“The surprising part is that Trump embraced this decision, and I would say that he knows what he is doing.”

title: ‘Hamas absolved itself from delivering opinion on future of Gaza’

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
The first to respond to Hamas’s announcement were the families of Israeli captives who are celebrating the news.

It took some time for the Israeli prime minister to react, welcoming and committing to the implementation of the first phase – the release of the Israeli captives.

What does this mean? It means that Israel must prepare its negotiation team to talk details, to talk maps, how the withdrawals will happen, and how the release of Israeli and Palestinian captives will happen.

And in the meantime, the Israeli army is warning people not to return to the north.

Al Jazeera’s Nour Odeh reports.

So it’s not a ceasefire, it’s not an end to the war, it’s almost a pause – but still very precarious and the hours ahead – as the momentum builds – will be very telling on which direction things will go.
